  "findings": [
    "ACDC rect law confirmed: d=rand is beneficial when n_ff/n_embd > ~5. Falcon3-10B (7.5×): +2.1% to +3.6%. Falcon3-3B (3.0×): -2.2% to -3.5%.",
    "d=0 (zero diagonal) outperforms d=rand for Falcon3-10B (+3.6% vs +2.1%): skipping weight reads is the dominant effect; FWHT of zero-filled buffer is cache-friendly.",
    "BitNet-2B (n_ff/n_embd=2.7×) shows marginal +1.7% with ACDC rect d=rand — within noise, not conclusive.",
    "L4 sparse float is +0% to +2% for small FFN (BitNet-2B/Falcon3-3B) but -17% to -19% for large FFN (Falcon3-10B): attention savings vanish when FFN dominates.",
    "L3 ACDC FFN (square, legacy): overhead grows with model depth (-2.8% BitNet-2B → -8.7% Falcon3-3B → -10.7% Falcon3-10B). FWHT lacks AVX2 throughput of I2_S GEMV.",
    "L5 HRR+cleanup > L5 raw only on Falcon3-10B (head_dim=256, d/N capacity ratio higher). head_dim=128 shows no cleanup benefit.",
    "ACDC rect target bottleneck identified: FFN weight reads dominate Falcon3-10B (720 MB/forward). ACDC rect reduces to 4.2 MB (170× less memory traffic).",
    "Next step: train with ACDC rect architecture (P6 gap) to get non-trivial d* and measure quality vs throughput tradeoff."
  ]
